    <main>
        <p>
  To understand why the delta function under an integral picks out a particular value of the integrand, it may help to think of it as the limit of a sequence of steps.
</p>

<p>
  Let <span set:html={K(`\\delta(t)`)}/> be the Dirac delta function. We can approximate it with a sequence of rectangular pulses <span set:html={K(`\\delta_n(t)`)} />:
</p>

<p>
  <span set:html={K(`
  \\delta_n(t) =
  \\begin{cases}
    h_n, & |t| \\le \\frac{w_n}{2} \\\\
    0, & |t| > \\frac{w_n}{2}
  \\end{cases}
  `)} />
</p>

<p>
  Each pulse has area 1:
  <span set:html={K(`\\int_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} \\delta_n(t) \\, dt = h_n w_n = 1`)} />
</p>

<p>
  In the limit, the delta function is obtained as:
  <span set:html={K(`\\delta(t) = \\lim_{n \\to \\infty} \\delta_n(t), \\quad w_n \\to 0, \\quad h_n \\to \\infty`)} />
</p>

<p>
  The key property under an integral is:
  <span set:html={K(`\\int_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} f(t) \\, \\delta(t-a) \\, dt = f(a)`)} />
  where <span set:html={K(`f(t)`)} /> is any continuous function.
</p>

<p>
  Each <span set:html={K(`\\delta_n(t-a)`)} /> is a pulse centered at <span set:html={K(`t=a`)} />, so in the limit, the integral “picks out” <span set:html={K(`f(a)`)} />.
  See a visual below
</p>


<p style="text-align: center;">
  <img src="https://books.physics.oregonstate.edu/GMM/images/deltaapprox.png" alt="Approximation of delta function by narrowing rectangular pulses" style="max-width: 100%; height: auto;" />
</p>
      
